04689nam a22007215i 9780813570624DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2014040074  a97808135706247 a10.36019/97808135706242doi  a(DE-B1597)526434  a(OCoLC)920692161  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV2863b.F75 2015 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.9/08209541 aFriedner, Michele Ilana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aValuing Deaf Worlds in Urban India /cMichele Ilana Friedner. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b1 photograph, 7 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNaming And Translation Practices -- tIntroduction: Deaf Turns, Deaf Orientations, And Deaf Development -- t1. Orienting From (Bad) Family To (Good) Friends -- t2. Converting To The Church Of Deaf Sociality -- t3. Circulation As Vocation -- t4. Deaf Bodies, Corporate Bodies -- t5. Enrolling Deafness In Multilevel Marketing Businesses -- tConclusion: India’S Deaf Futures/Reorienting The World -- tAppendix: Key Concepts From Indian Sign Language -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout The Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough it is commonly believed that deafness and disability limits a person in a variety of ways, Valuing Deaf Worlds in Urban India describes the two as a source of value in postcolonial India. Michele Friedner argues that the experiences of deaf people offer an important portrayal of contemporary self-making and sociality under new regimes of labor and economy in India. Friedner contends that deafness actually becomes a source of value for deaf Indians as they interact with nongovernmental organizations, with employers in the global information technology sector, and with the state. In contrast to previous political economic moments, deaf Indians increasingly depend less on the state for education and employment, and instead turn to novel and sometimes surprising spaces such as NGOs, multinational corporations, multilevel marketing businesses, and churches that attract deaf congregants. They also gravitate towards each other. Their social practices may be invisible to outsiders because neither the state nor their families have recognized Indian Sign Language as legitimate, but deaf Indians collectively learn sign language, which they use among themselves, and they also learn the importance of working within the structures of their communities to maximize their opportunities. Valuing Deaf Worlds in Urban India analyzes how diverse deaf people become oriented toward each other and disoriented from their families and other kinship networks. More broadly, this book explores how deafness, deaf sociality, and sign language relate to contemporary society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeaf culturezIndia. 0aDeafzIndia. 0aPeople with disabilitieszIndia. 0aSociology of disabilityzIndia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066615140uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357062440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813570624423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813570624.jpg  a978-3-11-066615-1  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK